I was inspired by other programmers' idea. So after I figured it out, I want to mark down my understanding.

Here is my code with some examples to help you understand linked list and loop.
Our goal is to find out the entry of the loop, as showed in the examples.
```
var findDuplicate = function(nums) {
    let slow = nums[0], fast = nums[nums[0]];

    //here fast moves two steps at a time
    while(slow!==fast){
    	slow = nums[slow];
    	fast = nums[nums[fast]];
    }
    fast=0;

    //here fast move one step at a time
    while(slow!==fast){
    	slow = nums[slow];
    	fast = nums[fast];
    }
    return slow;
};

// Examples:
// [1,4,3,5,2,2]
// 0->1->4->2->3->5->2->3->5->...
//          ^

// [1,3,2,1]
// 0->1->3->1->3->...
//    ^

// [3,4,6,5,1,1,2]
// 0->3->5->1->4->1->4->...
//          ^
```
Here is my understanding about finding the entry using linked list:
![image](https://s3-lc-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/users/lmiaoj/image_1527687950.png)

As we can see from the examples above, the linked list will eventually run into a loop.
When slow and fast first meet at m1, let's assume that the fast had passed **fLen**, and the slow had passed **sLen**, and the length of the loop is **LoopLen**,  then 
* **fLen - sLen = LoopLen * n** (n can be any integer >= 1)
* **fLen = sLen * 2**

so
* **sLen = LoopLen * n**

and because 
* **sLen = len + curve1 + LoopLen * n1** (n1 can be any integer, including 0)

so
* **len + curve1 = LoopLen * n2** (n2 can be any integer >= 1)

and because
* **curve1 + curve2 = LoopLen**

so, in the second loop, fast will re-begin at the begin point and moves one step at a time.
after
* fast moves **len**, and
* slow moves **curve2 + LoopLen * n3** (n3 can be any integer, including 0)

fast and slow will both reach the **entry point**.

