# **Find the cycle solution. O(n) time O(1) space**
The problem is simple once you know the trick. Check out [finding cycle in linked list](https://leetcode.com/problems/linked-list-cycle-ii/discuss/151434/2-c++-solutions.-Beat-100.-With-comments-proof-and-description.) for background as to how this finds the start of a cycle.

Basically we treat the array elements as an index to another element, this produces a kind of linked list starting at the first element. As each element is in the range [1, n] and there are n + 1 elements, each element will point to a valid index. A cycle will be created when two (or more) duplicates point to the same element. All that remains is to find the start of the cycle.

## **C++ Solution**
```
int findDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
  int slow = 0;
  int fast = 0;
  while ((slow = nums[slow]) != (fast = nums[nums[fast]]))
    ;
  slow = 0;
  while ((slow = nums[slow]) != (fast = nums[fast]))
    ;
  return slow;
}
```
I mean, I know it could get stupid a really ugly compact.
```
  int fast = nums[nums[0]];
  for (int slow = nums[0]; slow != fast; slow = nums[slow], fast = nums[nums[fast]]) ;
  for (int slow = 0; slow != fast; slow = nums[slow], fast = nums[fast]) ;
  return fast;
}
```		
But that's just dumb.
## **C Solution**
Pretty much exactly the same as c++
```c
int findDuplicate(int* nums, int numsSize){
  int slow = 0;
  int fast = 0;
  while ((slow = nums[slow]) != (fast = nums[nums[fast]])) /* Move slow one step, fast two */
    ;
  slow = 0;
  while ((slow = nums[slow]) != (fast = nums[fast])) /* Move both one step until they meet now */
    ;
  return slow;
}
```
## **Java Solution**
Pretty much exactly the same as c++
```java
public int findDuplicate(int[] nums) {
  int slow = 0;
  int fast = 0;
  while ((slow = nums[slow]) != (fast = nums[nums[fast]]))
    ;
  slow = 0;
  while ((slow = nums[slow]) != (fast = nums[fast]))
    ;
  return slow;
}
```
## **Python Solution**
You can't update the indexes as part of the while loop, so the python solution is slightly longer (though you could update slow and fast on the same line with python.
```python
def findDuplicate(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
  slow = nums[0];
  fast = nums[nums[0]]
  while slow != fast:
    slow = nums[slow]
    fast = nums[nums[fast]]
  slow = 0
  while slow != fast:
    slow = nums[slow]
    fast = nums[fast]
  return slow
  ```

# **Partition search. O(nlogn) time O(1) space**
An alternative solution is to brute force it, guessing possible values and checking if it is the duplicate. How to check though? One way is to use a simple flag, setting it on the first occurance of the target number and returning if the target is seen again. That only gives a true or false indication, can we do better?

If you consider the case of no duplicates, if we are targeting a number `n`, then we would expect there to be `n` numbers equal or below `n`. What about if there is a duplicate? Well if the duplicate is `n` or below, then our count would be over. If the count is equal or less, then the duplicate must be _above_ `n`. That sounds like something we can search on.

```
int findDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
  int lo = 0;
  int hi = nums.size() - 1;
  int mid;
  while (lo < hi) {
    mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
    // Count how many numbers are equal or below the mid, if it is lower than expected then the
    // duplicate must be in the upper partition, other wise it's in the lower partition.
    if (mid >= std::count_if(nums.begin(), nums.end(), [&mid] (int n) { return n <= mid; })) {
      lo = mid + 1;
    } else {
      hi = mid;
    }
  }
  return hi;
}
```

