solutions.content:
I've seen many solutions using Floyd's algorithm, a few solutions using binary search but none using the bonus approach mentioned at the end!

**Approach 1: Floyd's Algorithm**

Maintain 2 pointers, a tortoise moving one-step forward and a hare moving two-steps forward. You will need to spend time understanding this algorithms because at first it will seem like magic. I won't go into the depth here but you can read [this](https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/10360/floyds-cycle-detection-algorithm-determining-the-starting-point-of-cycle) page which gives a short explanation as to why it works. For a more in-depth explanation, read [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cycle_detection).

```cpp
int findDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
	int slow, fast;
	slow = fast = 0;

	// floyd's algorithm
	do {
		slow = nums[slow];
		fast = nums[nums[fast]];
	} while (slow != fast);

	// find the entrance to the cyle
	slow = 0;
	while (slow != fast) {
		slow = nums[slow];
		fast = nums[fast];
	}

	return slow;
}
```

**Complexity:**
* Time: `O(n)`
* Space: `O(1)`


**Approach 2: Binary Search**

We know the range of the values are form `1` to `n`. We can binary search this range to find the duplicate element. At each step, we compute the `number of values ≤ mid`, let's call this `x`. If `x` is greater than `mid`, then we know the range `1` to `mid` contains duplicates. If not, then the range `mid + 1` to `n` contains duplicates.

Using the property, we binary search on either the left side or the right side. Look into the implementation for more details.

```cpp
int findDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
	int mid, low = 1, high = nums.size();

	// helper function
	auto good = [&](int x) -> bool {
		int cnt = 0;
		for (int& num: nums)
			cnt += num <= x;
		return cnt > x;
	};

	// binary search
	while (low < high) {
		mid = (low + high) / 2;
		if (good(mid))
			high = mid;
		else
			low = mid + 1;
	}

	return high;
}
```

**Complexity:**
* Time: `O(n • log n)`
* Space: `O(1)`


**Bonus: Using the bit information**

This is perhaps the most different approach. Here, we keep track of the bit information in array called `bit`. For each _bit_ position from `0` to `31` (using zero-indexing), we count the number of ones present for each number from `1` to `n`. This array contains the count of ones in each bit position assuming there are no duplicates.

Now what happens if there is a duplicate? Let's say the duplicate is `11` or in binary `1011`. Then in each of the bit positions `{0, 1, 3}` there is an additional one.

From this, we get the following: count the number of ones in each _bit_ position from `0` to `31` for each number in nums. If the value of ones is greater than the actual count stored in `bit[i]`, then add one to the position `i`.

```cpp
int findDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
	int dup = 0;
	vector<int> bit(32);
	int n = nums.size() - 1;

	// precompute
	for (int b = 0; b < 32; b++)
		for (int x = 1; x <= n; x++)
			bit[b] += (x >> b) & 1;

	// find the duplicate
	for (int b = 0; b < 32; b++) {
		int cnt = 0;
		for (int& num: nums)
			cnt += (num >> b) & 1;
		dup |= (cnt > bit[b]) << b;
	}

	return dup;
}
```

**Complexity:**
* Time: `O(n • 32) = O(n)`
* Space: `O(32) = O(1)`

