class Solution {
    public int findDuplicate(int[] nums) {

        if(nums.length == 0)
            return -1;

        int[] hashmap = new int[32];
        int[] map = new int[32];

        Arrays.fill(hashmap, 0);
        Arrays.fill(map, 0);

        int n = nums.length;

		//Step 1
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++){
            int temp = i;
            int idx = 0;
            while(temp > 0){
                if((temp & 1) == 1)
                    hashmap[idx]++;
                temp = temp >> 1;
                idx ++;
            }
        }


		//Step 2
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
            int temp = nums[i];
            int idx = 0;
            while(temp > 0){
                if((temp & 1) == 1)
                    map[idx]++;
                temp = temp >> 1;
                idx++;
            }
        }

        int result = 0;

		//Step 3 and 4
        for(int i = 0; i < 32; i++){
            if(map[i] > hashmap[i])
                result = result | (1 << i);
        }

        return result;

    }
}
```

1.  First count the number of occurence of bit set to 1 at each bit position (i. e. from position 1 to position 32) for range 1 to n both inclusive, used int array "hashmap" to do so.
2.  Count the number of occurence of bit set to 1 at each bit position (i. e. from position 1 to position 32) for numbers given in the array, used int array "map" to do so.
3. If a number 'x' is repeated in the array then for each bit position 'pos' set to 1 in number 'x', map[pos] > hashmap[pos] holds true.
4. Using map[pos] > hashmap[pos], extract all the bit positions set to 1 in number 'x'.

