solutions.content:
**Intiution :** 
1. **One easy way** is to just calculate sum of left and right side and compare if it balances out everytime you jump to any array element. The issue with this approach would be it would take **O(n^2)** time complexity.
2. **Second way** is to know left and right sums of each element beforehand. To do that you can modify the array provided and exchange the elements with the sum of all elements till that index. 
	***For Ex: ( [1,5,-2,4] changes to [1,6,4,8] )***

	We can achieve this by doing **nums[i]=nums[i]+nums[i-1];**

	Then comes the **edge cases** like what if just **by excluding first or last element you get sum=0**, that would mean left and right are balanced. To achieve this you will see 2 ** if conditions** in the code.

```
class Solution {
    public int pivotIndex(int[] dp) {
        int n=dp.length;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            dp[i]+=dp[i-1];
        }
        if(dp[n-1]-dp[0]==0)
            return 0;
        for(int i=1;i<n-1;i++){
            if(dp[i-1]==dp[n-1]-dp[i])
                return i;
        }
        if(dp[n-2]==0)
            return n-1;
        return -1;
    }
}
```

**The above code runs with O(n) time complexity, If you liked the solution and it helps you understand the concept better do like the solution !
