class Solution {
    public int pivotIndex(int[] nums) {
        int left = 0, right;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
            right = 0;
            for(int j = i+1; j < nums.length; j++){
                right += nums[j];
            }            
            if(left == right){
                return i;
            }
            left += nums[i];
        }
        return -1;

    }
}

The pivotIndex function takes in an array nums and returns the index of the pivot point. The pivot point is the index where the sum of all numbers to the left is equal to the sum of all numbers to the right.

For example, if nums = [1, 7, 3, 6, 5, 6], the pivot index would be 3, because 1 + 7 = 3 + 6.

The code first sets a variable left to 0 and right to 0. It then loops through the array nums, calculating the sum of all numbers to the right of the current index i and storing it in the variable right.

If the current left and right values are equal, then the current index i is the pivot index and the function returns i. If not, it adds the current value in nums[i] to left and continues to the next iteration.

If the loop finishes and there was no pivot index found, the function returns -1.

